            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Wong is a product of San Francisco's Richmond District, born to a stoic father from Hong Kong who ran a small butcher shop and a second-generation Chinese-American mother who chose his decidedly non-traditional first name. Growing up amidst the city's fog and the scent of his father's shop, Marco learned the value of pragmatism and hard work. He was never a flashy student, but he was logical and observant, drawn to how things fit together. This led him to a practical path, earning his Bachelor's in Industrial Engineering from San Francisco State University.\n\nHe began his career on the factory floor of a Bay Area food processing plant, learning the machinery and the people who ran it. His ability to streamline processes without alienating the workforce saw him steadily promoted. Now, as an Operations Manager in a manufacturing facility in the Dogpatch, he\u2019s respected for knowing the name of every person on the line. He embodies a competence that feels like a relic from a pre-tech boom era.\n\nThe key turning point in Marco\u2019s life was not a promotion, but a personal system failure: an amicable but gutting divorce at 41. He had been so focused on providing that he had neglected the emotional mechanics of his marriage. The event forced a quiet introspection. He lives alone now, in a modest but meticulously maintained home in the Portola district.\n\nHis daily routine is a study in discipline. Up at 5:30 AM, coffee, and then the 5.5-mile drive in his reliable sedan before the traffic thickens. Evenings are for simple, home-cooked meals and trying to connect with his teenage daughter, who lives with her mother in the Sunset. They have dinner together every Wednesday, a ritual he cherishes.\n\nMarco\u2019s connection to San Francisco is deep and layered. He resents the impossible cost of living but finds solace in hiking the familiar trails of McLaren Park. His dreams are not of corporate ladders, but of personal repairs: rebuilding a stronger bond with his daughter and perhaps taking a long road trip through the national parks\u2014a quiet adventure far from the demands of production schedules. He aspires to a life of contentedness, a well-managed system of personal peace in the city that shaped him."
